# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: subresource-integrity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] The **`crossorigin`** attribute, valid on the `<audio>`, `<img>`, `<link>`, `<script>`, and `<video>` elements, provides support for CORS, defining how the element handles cross-origin requests, thereby enabling the configuration of the CORS requests for the element's fetched data.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] Depending on the element, the attribute can be a CORS settings attribute.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] The `crossorigin` content attribute on media elements is a CORS settings attribute.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] Request uses CORS headers and credentials flag is set to `'same-origin'`.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] There is no exchange of **user credentials** via cookies, client-side TLS certificates or HTTP authentication, unless destination is the same origin.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] Request uses CORS headers, credentials flag is set to `'include'` and **user credentials** are always included.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] Setting the attribute name to an empty value, like `crossorigin` or `crossorigin=""`, is the same as `anonymous`.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] An invalid keyword and an empty string will be handled as the `anonymous` keyword.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] By default (that is, when the attribute is not specified), CORS is not used at all.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] You can use the following `<script>` element to tell a browser to execute the `https://example.com/example-framework.js` script without sending user-credentials.
[src:subresource-integrity/attributes-crossorigin] The `use-credentials` value must be used when fetching a manifest that requires credentials, even if the file is from the same origin.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:subresource-integrity/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The **`<script>`** HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The `<script>` element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] For classic scripts, if the `async` attribute is present, then the classic script will be fetched in parallel to parsing and evaluated as soon as it is available.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] For module scripts, if the `async` attribute is present then the scripts and all their dependencies will be fetched in parallel to parsing and evaluated as soon as they are available.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This attribute allows the elimination of **parser-blocking JavaScript** where the browser would have to load and evaluate scripts before continuing to parse.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] `defer` has a similar effect in this case.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] If the attribute is specified with the `defer` attribute, the element will act as if only the `async` attribute is specified.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This is a boolean attribute: the presence of a boolean attribute on an element represents the true value, and the absence of the attribute represents the false value.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] See Browser compatibility for notes on browser support.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Specifies that you want the browser to send an `Attribution-Reporting-Eligible` header along with the script resource request.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] On the server-side this is used to trigger sending an `Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source` or `Attribution-Reporting-Register-Trigger` header in the response, to register a JavaScript-based attribution source or attribution trigger, respectively.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Which response header should be sent back depends on the value of the `Attribution-Reporting-Eligible` header that triggered the registration.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] See the Attribution Reporting API for more details.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This attribute explicitly indicates that certain operations should be blocked until the script has executed.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The operations that are to be blocked must be a space-separated list of blocking tokens.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Normal `script` elements pass minimal information to the `window.onerror` for scripts which do not pass the standard CORS checks.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] To allow error logging for sites which use a separate domain for static media, use this attribute.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] See CORS settings attributes for a more descriptive explanation of its valid arguments.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This Boolean attribute is set to indicate to a browser that the script is meant to be executed after the document has been parsed, but before firing `DOMContentLoaded` event.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Scripts with the `defer` attribute will prevent the `DOMContentLoaded` event from firing until the script has loaded and finished evaluating.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The `defer` attribute has no effect on module scripts — they defer by default.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Scripts with the `defer` attribute will execute in the order in which they appear in the document.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] `async` has a similar effect in this case.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] If the attribute is specified with the `async` attribute, the element will act as if only the `async` attribute is specified.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching an external script.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Fetch the external script at a high priority relative to other external scripts.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Fetch the external script at a low priority relative to other external scripts.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Don't set a preference for the fetch priority.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] It is used if no value or an invalid value is set.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This attribute contains one or more hashes of the script.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] It is used to ensure that the content of the script is what the developer expects it to be, and has not been replaced with a malicious script in a supply chain attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The attribute must not be specified when the `src` attribute is absent.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This Boolean attribute is set to indicate that the script should not be executed in browsers that support ES modules — in effect, this can be used to serve fallback scripts to older browsers that do not support modular JavaScript code.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] A cryptographic nonce (number used once) to allow scripts in a script-src Content-Security-Policy.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The server must generate a unique nonce value each time it transmits a policy.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] It is critical to provide a nonce that cannot be guessed as bypassing a resource's policy is otherwise trivial.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This attribute specifies the URI of an external script; this can be used as an alternative to embedding a script directly within a document.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This attribute indicates the type of script represented.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Indicates that the script is a "classic script", containing JavaScript code.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Authors are encouraged to omit the attribute if the script refers to JavaScript code rather than specify a MIME type.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] JavaScript MIME types are listed in the IANA media types specification.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This value indicates that the body of the element contains an import map.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The import map is a JSON object that developers can use to control how the browser resolves module specifiers when importing JavaScript modules.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This value causes the code to be treated as a JavaScript module.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The processing of the script contents is deferred.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The `charset` and `defer` attributes have no effect.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] For information on using `module`, see our JavaScript modules guide.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Unlike classic scripts, module scripts require the use of the CORS protocol for cross-origin fetching.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This value indicates that the body of the element contains speculation rules.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Speculation rules take the form of a JSON object that determine what resources should be prefetched or prerendered by the browser.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] This is part of the Speculation Rules API.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The embedded content is treated as a data block, and won't be processed by the browser.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Developers must use a valid MIME type that is not a JavaScript MIME type to denote data blocks.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] All of the other attributes will be ignored, including the `src` attribute.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] If present, its value must be an ASCII case-insensitive match for `utf-8`.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] It's unnecessary to specify the `charset` attribute, because documents must use UTF-8, and the `script` element inherits its character encoding from the document.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Like the `type` attribute, this attribute identifies the scripting language in use.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] Unlike the `type` attribute, however, this attribute's possible values were never standardized.
[src:subresource-integrity/elements-script] The `type` attribute should be used instead.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-2 includes significant changes from its predecessor, **SHA-1**.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-256 and SHA-512 are hash functions whose digests are eight 32-bit and 64-bit words, respectively.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] They use different shift amounts and additive constants, but their structures are otherwise virtually identical, differing only in the number of rounds.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-224 and SHA-384 are truncated versions of SHA-256 and SHA-512 respectively, computed with different initial values.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-512/224 and SHA-512/256 are also truncated versions of SHA-512, but the initial values are generated using the method described in Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) PUB 180-4.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-2 was first published by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as a U.S. federal standard.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The SHA-2 family of algorithms are patented in the U.S.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The United States has released the patent under a royalty-free license.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] As of 2024, the **SHA-2** cryptographic hash function remains secure against known attacks, including those from quantum computers.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] With the publication of FIPS PUB 180-2, NIST added three additional hash functions in the SHA family.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The algorithms are collectively known as SHA-2, named after their digest lengths (in bits): SHA-256, SHA-384, and SHA-512.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The algorithms were first published in 2001 in the draft FIPS PUB 180-2, at which time public review and comments were accepted.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In August 2002, FIPS PUB 180-2 became the new Secure Hash Standard, replacing FIPS PUB 180-1, which was released in April 1995.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The updated standard included the original SHA-1 algorithm, with updated technical notation consistent with that describing the inner workings of the SHA-2 family.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In February 2004, a change notice was published for FIPS PUB 180-2, specifying an additional variant, SHA-224, defined to match the key length of two-key Triple DES.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In October 2008, the standard was updated in FIPS PUB 180-3, including SHA-224 from the change notice, but otherwise making no fundamental changes to the standard.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The primary motivation for updating the standard was relocating security information about the hash algorithms and recommendations for their use to Special Publications 800-107 and 800-57.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Detailed test data and example message digests were also removed from the standard, and provided as separate documents.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In March 2012, the standard was updated in FIPS PUB 180-4, adding the hash functions SHA-512/224 and SHA-512/256, and describing a method for generating initial values for truncated versions of SHA-512.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Additionally, a restriction on padding the input data prior to hash calculation was removed, allowing hash data to be calculated simultaneously with content generation, such as a real-time video or audio feed.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Padding the final data block must still occur prior to hash output.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In July 2012, NIST revised SP800-57, which provides guidance for cryptographic key management.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The publication disallowed creation of digital signatures with a hash security lower than 112 bits after 2013.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The previous revision from 2007 specified the cutoff to be the end of 2010.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In August 2012, NIST revised SP800-107 in the same manner.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In March 2023, NIST announced its decision to revise FIPS 180-4.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] FIPS 180-5 will remove the SHA-1 specification, add guidance from SP 800-107, and include editorial updates.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The NIST hash function competition selected a new hash function, SHA-3, in 2012.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The SHA-3 algorithm is not derived from SHA-2.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The SHA-2 hash function is implemented in some widely used security applications and protocols, including TLS and SSL, PGP, SSH, S/MIME, and IPsec.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The inherent computational demand of SHA-2 algorithms has driven the proposal of more efficient solutions, such as those based on application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) hardware accelerators.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-256 is used for authenticating Debian software packages and in the DKIM message signing standard; SHA-512 is part of a system to authenticate archival video from the International Criminal Tribunal of the Rwandan genocide.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Linux distributions usually use 512-bit SHA-2 for secure password hashing.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Several cryptocurrencies, including Bitcoin, use SHA-256 for verifying transactions and calculating proof of work or proof of stake.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The rise of ASIC SHA-2 accelerator chips has led to the use of scrypt-based proof-of-work schemes.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In both 4G and 5G mobile networks, HMAC-SHA-256 is utilized as a key derivation function (KDF) to generate cryptographic keys essential for securing communications.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] This process is defined in the 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) Technical Specifications TS 33.401 and TS 33.501, which outline the security architecture and procedures for these networks.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-1, SHA-2, and SHA-3 are the Secure Hash Algorithms required by law for use in certain U.S.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Government applications, including use within other cryptographic algorithms and protocols, for the protection of sensitive unclassified information.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] FIPS PUB 180-1 also encouraged adoption and use of SHA-1 by private and commercial organizations.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-1 is being retired for most government uses; the U.S.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] National Institute of Standards and Technology says, "NIST recommends that federal agencies transition away from SHA-1 for all applications as soon as possible.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Federal agencies should use SHA-2 or SHA-3 as an alternative to SHA-1.".
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] NIST's directive that U.S. government agencies ought to, but not explicitly must, stop uses of SHA-1 after 2010 was hoped to accelerate migration away from SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The SHA-2 functions were not quickly adopted initially, despite better security than SHA-1.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Reasons might include lack of support for SHA-2 on systems running Windows XP SP2 or older and a lack of perceived urgency since SHA-1 collisions had not yet been found.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The Google Chrome team announced a plan to make their web browser gradually stop honoring SHA-1-dependent TLS certificates over a period from late 2014 and early 2015.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Similarly, Microsoft announced that Internet Explorer and Edge [Legacy] would stop honoring public SHA-1-signed TLS certificates from February 2017.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Mozilla disabled SHA-1 in Firefox during early January 2016, but had to re-enable it temporarily via an update, after problems with web-based user interfaces of some router models and security appliances.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] For a hash function for which *L* is the number of bits in the message digest, finding a message that corresponds to a given message digest can always be done using a brute force search in 2*L* evaluations.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] This is called a preimage attack and may or may not be practical depending on *L* and the particular computing environment.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The second criterion, finding two different messages that produce the same message digest, known as a collision, requires on average only 2*L*/2 evaluations using a birthday attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Some of the applications that use cryptographic hashes, such as password storage, are only minimally affected by a collision attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Constructing a password that works for a given account requires a preimage attack, as well as access to the hash of the original password (typically in the `shadow` file) which may or may not be trivial.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Reversing password encryption (e.g., to obtain a password to try against a user's account elsewhere) is not made possible by the attacks.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] In the case of document signing, an attacker could not simply fake a signature from an existing document—the attacker would have to produce a pair of documents, one innocuous and one damaging, and get the private key holder to sign the innocuous document.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] There are practical circumstances in which this is possible; until the end of 2008, it was possible to create forged SSL certificates using an MD5 collision which would be accepted by widely used web browsers.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Increased interest in cryptographic hash analysis during the SHA-3 competition produced several new attacks on the SHA-2 family, the best of which are given in the table below.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Only the collision attacks are of practical complexity; none of the attacks extend to the full round hash function.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] At FSE 2012, researchers at Sony gave a presentation suggesting pseudo-collision attacks could be extended to 52 rounds on SHA-256 and 57 rounds on SHA-512 by building upon the biclique pseudo-preimage attack.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Implementations of all FIPS-approved security functions can be officially validated through the CMVP program, jointly run by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and the Communications Security Establishment (CSE).
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] For informal verification, a package to generate a high number of test vectors is made available for download on the NIST site; the resulting verification, however, does not replace the formal CMVP validation, which is required by law for certain applications.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] As of December 2013, there are over 1300 validated implementations of SHA-256 and over 900 of SHA-512, with only 5 of them being capable of handling messages with a length in bits not a multiple of eight while supporting both variants.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Hash values of an empty string (i.e., a zero-length input text).
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Even a small change in the message will (with overwhelming probability) result in a different hash, due to the avalanche effect.
