[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The performance numbers labeled 'x86' were running using 32-bit code on 64-bit processors, whereas the 'x86-64' numbers are native 64-bit code.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] While SHA-256 is designed for 32-bit calculations, it does benefit from code optimized for 64-bit processors on the x86 architecture.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] 32-bit implementations of SHA-512 are significantly slower than their 64-bit counterparts.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Variants of both algorithms with different output sizes will perform similarly, since the message expansion and compression functions are identical, and only the initial hash values and output sizes are different.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The best implementations of MD5 and SHA-1 perform between 4.5 and 6 cycles per byte on modern processors.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] Testing was performed by the University of Illinois at Chicago on their hydra8 system running an Intel Xeon E3-1275 V2 at a clock speed of 3.5 GHz, and on their hydra9 system running an AMD A10-5800K APU at a clock speed of 3.8 GHz.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The referenced cycles per byte speeds above are the median performance of an algorithm digesting a 4,096 byte message using the SUPERCOP cryptographic benchmarking software.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] The MiB/s performance is extrapolated from the CPU clockspeed on a single core; real-world performance will vary due to a variety of factors.
[src:subresource-integrity/sha-2] SHA-256 and SHA-512 are vulnerable to a length extension attack, but SHA-384 and SHA-256/512 are not vulnerable because their output is a truncated version of their internal state.
[src:subresource-integrity/subresource-integrity] To use SRI, a website author wishing to include a resource from a third party can specify a cryptographic hash of the resource in addition to the location of the resource.
[src:subresource-integrity/subresource-integrity] Browsers fetching the resource can then compare the hash provided by the website author with the hash computed from the resource.
[src:subresource-integrity/subresource-integrity] If the hashes don't match, the resource is discarded.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] The **`digest()`** method of the `SubtleCrypto` interface generates a *digest* of the given data, using the specified hash function.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] A digest is a short fixed-length value derived from some variable-length input.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] Cryptographic digests should exhibit collision-resistance, meaning that it's hard to come up with two different inputs that have the same digest value.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] It takes as its arguments an identifier for the digest algorithm to use and the data to digest.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] It returns a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the digest.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] Note that this API does not support streaming input: you must read the entire input into memory before passing it into the digest function.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] This may be a string or an object with a single property `name` that is a string.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] The string names the hash function to use.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] An `ArrayBuffer`, a `TypedArray` or a `DataView` object containing the data to be digested.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] A `Promise` that fulfills with an `ArrayBuffer` containing the digest.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] Digest algorithms, also known as hash functions, transform an arbitrarily large block of data into a fixed-size output, usually much shorter than the input.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] They have a variety of applications in cryptography.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] For more examples of using the `digest()` API, see Non-cryptographic uses of SubtleCrypto.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] The digest is returned as an `ArrayBuffer`, but for comparison and display digests are often represented as hex strings.
[src:subresource-integrity/subtlecrypto-digest] The above example uses `Uint8Array.toHex()`, which became available in 2025.
